land":"Moray, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1335–1381":"1335–1381","1345–1365":"1345–1365","1340–1364":"1340–1364","1360–1412":"1360–1412","1364–1414":"1364–1414","1365–1410":"1365–1410","1300–1372":"1300–1372","1315–1350":"1315–1350","before 1335":"before 1335","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","Abt 1372":"about 1372","1315":"1315","1414":"1414","1335":"1335","1412":"1412","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1364":"1364","about 1365":"about 1365","about 1364":"about 1364","Innes, Morayshire, Schotland":"Elginshire, Scotland","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Abbey, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Abbey, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Elginshire, Scotland","Moray, Scotland":"Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Innes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McInnis  , from Gaelic <b>Mag Aonghuis</b> ‘son of Aonghus’.","Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Innes in Urquhart (Morayshire), named from Gaelic <i>inis</i> ‘island’.","English: variant of   Ince  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Inniss","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Ince","meanings":["habitational name from Ince in Makerfield (Lancashire), Ince (Cheshire), or Ince Blundell (Lancashire). The placenames derive from Proto-Welsh <i>ïnïs</i> ‘island’.","possibly a post-medieval West Midlands variant of <b>Hints</b>, a habitational name from either of two places called Hints (Staffordshire, Shropshire). The placenames probably derive from Proto-Welsh <i>hïnt</i> ‘way, path’ + Middle English plural <i>-es</i>.","possibly a variant with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i> of <i>Inn</i>, from residence at an <i>inn</i> or <i>inns</i>, from Middle English <i>in</i> (singular) or <i>innes</i> (plural) ‘tavern, lodging(s), tenement(s)’. There seems also to have been some confusion with Scottish   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Inch","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: perhaps, at least in some cases, a variant of   Ince  .","English: variant of   Hinch  ."]},{"name":"McInnis","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aonghuis</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Aonghus</i> (see   Angus  ). See also   McInnes  , compare Irish   McGinnis  ."]},{"name":"Innis","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: variant of   Ince  ."]},{"name":"Inness","meanings":["Scottish (Durham and Northumberland): variant of   Innes  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Innes 8th of Innes - of that Ilk was born in 1335, in Scotland, his father, William de Innes 7th of Innes - of that Ilk, was 36 and his mother, Margaret Leslie, was 20. He died in 1381, in Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1335–1381":"1335–1381","1345–1365":"1345–13